### Media and Arts: A Cultural Canvas

Lucknow has left an indelible mark on the [Hindi film industry](/Bollywood), being the birthplace of esteemed poet, dialogue writer, and scriptwriter [K. P. Saxena](/K._P._Saxena), as well as Suresh Chandra Shukla. The city also produced veteran Bollywood and Bengali film actor [Pahari Sanyal], who hailed from the prominent Sanyal family of Lucknow. Numerous films have utilized Lucknow as their backdrop, including Vinod Kumar's 1968 film [Mere Huzoor](/Mere_Huzoor), [Shashi Kapoor](/Shashi_Kapoor)'s [Junoon (1978 film)](/Junoon_(1978_film)), Muzaffar Ali's critically acclaimed [Umrao Jaan (1981 film)](/Umrao_Jaan_(1981_film)) and [Gaman](/Gaman), and [Satyajit Ray](/Satyajit_Ray)'s masterpiece [Shatranj ke khiladi](/Shatranj_ke_khiladi). [Ismail Merchant](/Ismail_Merchant)'s [Shakespeare Wallah](/Shakespeare_Wallah), [Paa (film)](/Paa_(film)), the 2022 Hindi feature film [Vikram Vedha (2022 film)](/Vikram_Vedha_(2022_film)), and Shailendra Pandey's [JD (film)](/JD_(film)) are among other productions filmed in or around the city. In the film [Gadar: Ek Prem Katha](/Gadar:_Ek_Prem_Katha), Lucknow was used to represent [Pakistan](/Pakistan), with locations such as Lal Pul and the Taj Hotel featured. The [Rumi Darwaza](/Rumi_Darwaza) was a notable setting in [Tanu Weds Manu](/Tanu_Weds_Manu). Portions of films like [Ladies vs Ricky Bahl](/Ladies_vs_Ricky_Bahl), [Bullett Raja](/Bullett_Raja), [Ishaqzaade](/Ishaqzaade), [Ya Rab](/Ya_Rab), and [Dabangg 2](/Dabangg_2) were also shot in Lucknow or its vicinity. A significant part of the Bollywood movie [Daawat-e-Ishq], starring [Aditya Roy Kapur](/Aditya_Roy_Kapur) and [Parineeti Chopra](/Parineeti_Chopra), was filmed in the city. The Indian TV drama [Baawre], which aired on the [Life OK](/Life_OK) channel, was also set in Lucknow. The government has announced plans to develop two film cities in the capital.

The news channel [Bharat Samachar] is headquartered in Lucknow. Prominent newspaper publications in the city include [Amar Ujala](/Amar_Ujala), [Dainik Jagran](/Dainik_Jagran), [Hindustan Times](/Hindustan_Times), [The Times of India](/The_Times_of_India), and [Dainik Bhaskar](/Dainik_Bhaskar).

[The Pioneer](/The_Pioneer_(newspaper)), headquartered in Lucknow and established in 1865, holds the distinction of being the second-oldest English-language newspaper in India still in publication. The country's first prime minister, [Jawaharlal Nehru](/Jawaharlal_Nehru), founded The National Herald in the city prior to World War II, with [Manikonda Chalapathi Rau](/Manikonda_Chalapathi_Rau) serving as its editor.

One of the earliest [All India Radio](/Akashvani_(radio_broadcaster)) stations has been operational in Lucknow since 1938. FM radio transmission commenced in Lucknow in 2000, and the city currently hosts the following FM radio stations:

